1.2 Temperature

1.2.1 Mean Maximum Temperature

# Assuming that 'dates' is a vector of your dates and 'temps' is a vector of your temperatures.
# Here's how you can combine them into a data frame.

date_strings <-WEA.H$Date  # up to "2024-02"
temps <- WEA.H$Monthly.Mean.Maximum.Temperature..degF. # all your temperature values

# Create a data frame
data <- data.frame(
  Date = as.Date(paste0(date_strings, "-01")), # Assuming each date is the first of the month
  Temperature = temps
)

# Calculate linear model
model <- lm(Temperature ~ Date, data = data)

# Calculate the correlation coefficient between the two variables
cor_coefficient <- cor(data$Temperature, as.numeric(data$Date))

# Create the plot using ggplot2
p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = Date, y = Temperature)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) + # add the line chart
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red", se = FALSE) + # add the linear regression line
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Year (1954 - 2024)", y = "Temperature (Â°F)", title = "Monthly Maximum Temperature Trends in Homer, AK") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + # center the plot title
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("RÂ² = %.4f, Correlation = %.4f", summary(model)$r.squared, cor_coefficient)),
            x = Inf, y = Inf, hjust = 1.1, vjust = 1.1, size = 4, color = "darkgreen")

# Print the plot
print(p)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

2 Annual Weather Records

Annual Weather Records in Homer, Alaska from 1954 to 2024

2.1 Average Temperature

date_strings <-WEA.H$Date  # up to "2024-02"
temps <- WEA.H$Monthly.Average.Mean.Temperature..degF.

# Create a data frame from the monthly data
monthly_data <- data.frame(
  Date = as.Date(paste0(date_strings, "-01")),
  Temperature = temps
)

# Calculate the yearly average temperature
yearly_data <- monthly_data %>%
  mutate(Year = format(Date, "%Y")) %>% # Extract the year from the Date
  group_by(Year) %>% # Group by the extracted year
  summarise(Avg_Temperature = mean(Temperature)) # Calculate the average

# Filter out the data for the year 2024
yearly_data <- yearly_data %>% 
  filter(Year != "2024")

# Calculate a linear model for the yearly averages
model_yearly <- lm(Avg_Temperature ~ as.numeric(Year), data = yearly_data)

# Compute the correlation coefficient
cor_coefficient_yearly <- cor(yearly_data$Avg_Temperature, as.numeric(yearly_data$Year))

# Plot the data with ggplot2
p_yearly <- ggplot(yearly_data, aes(x = as.numeric(Year), y = Avg_Temperature)) +
  geom_point() + # add points for each year
  geom_line() + # connect points with lines
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red", se = FALSE) + # add the regression line
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Year (1954 - 2023)", y = "Temperature (Â°F)", 
       title = "Average Annual Temperature Trends in Homer, AK") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + # center the plot title
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("RÂ² = %.4f, Correlation = %.4f", 
                                summary(model_yearly)$r.squared, 
                                cor_coefficient_yearly)), 
            x = Inf, y = Inf, hjust = 1.1, vjust = 1.1, size = 4, color = "darkgreen")

# Print the plot
print(p_yearly)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
